<div id="c8">
<p>Isn&#8217;t it at least as reasonable to assume that anything we still listen to (or read or view) after a few centuries is well adapted? That the greatest work by Shakespeare or Mozart or Michelangelo comes closer to approaching perfection than the vast majority of what&#8217;s currently being produced?</p>

<p>The same argument can be made for Lisp or C: they may not be perfect, and many people produce ill-advised programs in Lisp or C, just as the pianist you saw in Chicago may well have flubbed notes or had questionable timing. But if you&#8217;re going to try to make an argument for the best programming languages currently available, don&#8217;t you first have to explain why so many people who are trained to appreciate languages&#8217; subtleties still use Lisp and C? To me at least, that seems more reasonable than pointing to a straw man&#8217;s iffy code and deciding that Croma is the best programming language yet created by humans.</p>

<p>I understand your argument: Croma has benefitted from all the languages that came before it. But it will take decades before we&#8217;ll even be able to make a reasonable guess as to whether it&#8217;s a 100-year language or just the latest Aimee Mann record. If you were betting on music that will still be appreciated for its beauty 100 years from now, would you bet on Bach or Mann? And if you were betting on a computer language that would still be used in 20 years (let&#8217;s try to keep the ratios reasonable), would you bet on Lisp or Croma?</p>

