<p>The &#8216;reasonable assumption&#8217; that leads to old stuff being good is simple: survival of the fittest.  There must be untold millions of melodies that haven&#8217;t survived to the present day, or if so are buried in archives.  If any of them were really really good, don&#8217;t you think they&#8217;d still be well known?  Conversely, it&#8217;s a fair assumption that thoese works that <em>have</em> survived and managed to keep people&#8217;s attention for a few hundred years are likely to be pretty good.</p>

