<div id="c32">
<p>I like your blog, for what it&#8217;s worth.  In any case, you seem frustrated that music isn&#8217;t universally understood or appreciated despite the genetic similarity between authors and listeners.  But that doesn&#8217;t take into account cultural factors, such as language and the meanings we attach to symbols.  Sure, Chomsky demonstrated that all languages are composed of essentially the same stuff, but that doesn&#8217;t mean I can begin to appreciate a Russian poem without knowing Russian, to use an extreme example.  Some symbols don&#8217;t need a lot of explanation (e.g. a smile on a face or the sound of a baby crying).  But that doesn&#8217;t mean, for example, a pop song can&#8217;t more eloquently communicate a topical idea between a group of teenagers than, say, Bach.</p>

